'''Hovhannes Draskhanakerttsi''' ({{lang-hy|Հովհաննես Դրասխանակերտցի}}, John of Drasxanakert, i.e. [[Gyumri]], various spellings) was [[Catholicos of Armenia]] from 897 to 925, and a noted chronicler and historian. He is called '''John V the Historian''', and is known for his ''History of Armenia''.<ref>The title ''Patmutiun Hayots'' is generic.</ref><ref>[http://www.umd.umich.edu/dept/armenian/papazian/armenians.html ''... an important source on the Arab period...'']</ref> It was printed at the end of the seventeenth century.<ref>In [http://armenianstudies.csufresno.edu/faculty/kouymjian/articles/lazar.htm], under John Catholicos.</ref> There is a recent English translation (1987) by Krikor Maksoudian.
After returning the Catholicosate to [[Dvin (ancient city)|Dvin]] since it had been reclaimed from the Arabs, he moved it again to [[Vaspurakan]] around 924. According to local traditions, Hovhannes was buried in Vaspurakan at either Joroy Vank or in the monastery of [[Akhtamar]].
