{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2016}} {{Use Indian English|date=January 2016}}{{infobox Royalty|image=The sage Vyasa and the king Janamejaya..jpg|caption=The sage [[Vyasa]] and King Janamejaya|title=Kuru King|predecessor=[[Parikshit]]|successor=Asvmedhadatta|issue=Śatáníka|father=[[Parikshit]]|mother=[[Madravti]]}}
'''Janamejaya''' ({{lang-sa|जनमेजय}}) was a [[Kuru (kingdom)|Kuru]] king who reigned during the Middle [[Vedic period]] (12th-9th centuries BCE).<ref>[[Michael Witzel]] (1989), ''Tracing the Vedic dialects'' in ''Dialectes dans les litteratures Indo-Aryennes'' ed. [[Colette Caillat|Caillat]], Paris, 97–265.</ref> Along with his father and predecessor [[Parikshit]], he played a decisive role in the consolidation of the Kuru state, the arrangement of [[Vedas|Vedic hymns]] into collections, and the development of the orthodox [[srauta]] ritual, transforming the Kuru realm into the dominant political and cultural center of northern [[India]]. He also appears as a figure in later legends and traditions, the [[Mahabharata]] and the [[Puranas]].
== In Vedic Literature== Janamejaya is mentioned as a great king and conqueror in a number of late [[Vedas|Vedic texts]]. The ''[[Aitareya Brahmana]]'' (VIII.21) states that his priest Tura Kāvasheya anointed him with the Aindra Mahabhisheka (great anointing of [[Indra]]). The ''[[Shatapatha Brahmana]]'' mentions that he performed an ''[[ashvamedha]]'' (horse sacrifice), for getting himself rid of the ''Brahmahatya'' (sin associated with killing of a [[Brahmin]]), and the priest who performed it for him was Indrota Daivapa [[Shaunaka]] at a place named Āsandīvat.<ref name=":0" />
== Historicity == [[File:Late_Vedic_Culture_(1100-500_BCE).png|link=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Late_Vedic_Culture_(1100-500_BCE).png|right|thumb|[[Kuru Kingdom|Kuru]] and other kingdoms of the [[Vedic period]]]] [[Hem Chandra Raychaudhuri|H.C. Raychaudhuri]] dates [[Parikshit]], his father, in ninth century BC.{{sfn|Raychaudhuri|2006|pp=29-30}} [[Michael Witzel]] dates the Pārikṣita Dynasty of the Kuru Kingdom to the 12th-11th centuries BC.<ref>Michael Witzel (1989), [http://www.people.fas.harvard.edu/~witzel/dialects.pdf ''Tracing the Vedic dialects''], p.141</ref>
Only one Janamejaya is mentioned in Vedic literature; however, post-Vedic literature (Mahabharata and Puranas) seems to indicate the existence of two kings by this name, one who lived before the [[Kurukshetra War]] was an ancestor to the [[Pandavas]], and one who lived later and was a descendant.<ref name=":0">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=z3ksBrWoZm0C&pg=PA86&lpg=PA86&dq=Janamejaya+in+vedas&source=bl&ots=uxlT3X0OQt&sig=nolhfblCyVqKdB1ObUXLIj0_vXY&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjGzLGrnv_YAhXLpZQKHSdiDkcQ6AEIeDAO#v=onepage&q=Janamejaya%20in%20vedas&f=false|title=Vedic Civilization|last=Pruthi|first=Raj|date=2004|publisher=Discovery Publishing House|isbn=9788171418756|language=en}}</ref> Historian [[H. C. Raychaudhuri]] believes that the second Janamejaya's description better corresponds to the Vedic king, whereas the information available about first is scanty and inconsistent, but Raychaudhuri questions whether there were actually two distinct kings. He suggests that there "is an intrusion into the genealogical texts" of the late, post-Vedic tradition, which also has two of Janamejaya's father Parikshit, possibly "invented by genealogists to account for anachronisms" in the later parts of the Mahabharata, as "a bardic duplication of the same original individual regarding whose exact place in the Kuru genealogy no unanimous tradition had survived."<ref>Raychaudhuri (1996), pp.13-19</ref>{{refn|group=note|Also, Witzel (1995) only refers to one Parikshit and one Janamejaya.}}
Four copper-plate grant inscriptions purportedly issued during Janamejaya's reign were discovered in the 20th century, but were proved to be fake by historians.<ref>{{cite book |author=Richard Salomon |title=Indian Epigraphy: A Guide to the Study of Inscriptions in Sanskrit, Prakrit, and the Other Indo-Aryan Languages |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=t-4RDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA167 |year=1998 |publisher=Oxford University Press, USA |isbn=978-0-19-509984-3 |page=167 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |author=Shankar Goyal |title=History writing of early India: new discoveries and approaches |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pS9uAAAAMAAJ |year=1996 |publisher=Kusumanjali |oclc=34752382 |page=1}}</ref>
== In Puranic Literature == He was the son of King [[Parikshit]] and Queen Madravati according to the [[Mahabharata]] (I.95.85), but according to the [[Bhagavata Purana]] (I.xvi.2), his mother was Iravati, daughter of [[Uttara (Mahābhārata)|Uttara]].{{sfn|Raychaudhuri|2006|p=15, 35n}} He was the grandson of [[Abhimanyu]] and the great-grandson of [[Arjuna]], the valiant warrior hero of the [[Mahābhārata]]. He ascended to the Kuru throne following the death of his father. His significance comes as the listener of the first narration of the Mahābhārata, narrated by [[Vaishampayana]], pupil of [[Vyasa]]. According to the [[Vayu Purana]] and the [[Matsya Purana]], there was a dispute between him and Vaishampayana. Possibly, as its aftermath, he abdicated and his son Shatanika succeeded him.<ref>Misra, V.S. (2007). Ancient Indian Dynasties, Mumbai: Bharatiya Vidya Bhavan, {{ISBN|81-7276-413-8}}, p.278</ref> According to the [[Purana]]s,
=== In Mahabharata === In [[Mahabharata]], Janmejaya was mentioned as having six able brothers viz, Kakshasena, Ugrasena, Chitrasena, Indrasena, Sushena and Nakhaysena.<ref>''Journal of the Department of Letters'' by University of Calcutta (Dept. of Letters),Publ.Calcutta University Press, 1923, p2</ref> The initial chapters of the epic narrates various aspects of his life including his conquest of [[Taxila|Takshasila]] and about his encounter with Naga Takshaka. He wanted to exterminate the race of Nagas, since Takshaka was responsible for the death of his father Parikshit. [[File:Kashyapa_alive_tree_what_is_burnt_by_Takshak_(_near_Pond_)_and_parikshit_bitten_by_Takshak.jpg|link=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Kashyapa_alive_tree_what_is_burnt_by_Takshak_(_near_Pond_)_and_parikshit_bitten_by_Takshak.jpg|thumb|parikshit bitten by Takshak from Birla razmnama.]] Emperor Janmejay was responsible for the retelling of the famous epic ''[[Mahābhārata]]'', a story of Janmejay's ancestors from the time of [[Bharata (Mahabharata)|Bharata]] up to the great [[Kurukshetra]] war between his great-grandfathers the [[Pandavas]] and their paternal cousins the [[Kauravas]]. The Mahabharata states that it was recited to Janmejay at the ''sarpa satra'' (snake sacrifice) by the sage [[Vaishampayana]] to whom it had been imparted by his perceptor [[Vedavyasa]],<ref>Vaidya P.L. and A.D. Pusalkar (1962, reprint 2003). ''The Mahabharata: Its History and Character'' in S. Radhakrishnan (ed.) ''The Cultural Heritage of India'', Vol.II, Kolkata:The Ramakrishna Mission Institute of Culture, {{ISBN|81-85843-03-1}}, p.60</ref> after he asked [[Vaishampayana]] about his ancestors.
=== Sarpa satra (snake sacrifice) === [[File:Snakesacrifice.jpg|link=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Snakesacrifice.jpg|thumb|The snake sacrifice of Janmejay, as [[Astika (mythology)|Astika]] tries to stop it.]] {{main|Sarpa Satra}}Emperor Janmejay ascended to the throne of [[Hastinapura]] upon the death of his father [[Parikshit]]. According to legend, Parikshit, the lone descendant of the House of [[Pandu]], had died of snakebite. He had been cursed by a sage to die so, the curse having been consummated by the serpent-chieftain [[Takshak]]. Janmejay bore a deep grudge against the serpents for this act, and thus decided to wipe them out altogether. He attempted this by performing a great ''Sarpa satra'' – a sacrifice that would destroy all living serpents. At that time, a learned sage named [[Astika (mythology)|Astika]], a boy in age, came and interfered. His mother [[Manasa]] was a Naga and his father a [[Brahmin]]. Janmejay had to listen to the words of the learned Astika and set the then-imprisoned Takshaka free. He also stopped the massacre of the Nagas and ended all enmity with them (1,56). From that time onward, the Nagas and Kurus lived in peace. The mass sacrifice was started on the banks of the river Arind at Bardan, now Known as Parham, a corrupt form of [[Parikshitgarh]].{{citation needed|date=April 2016}} A masonry tank (reservoir) said to have been built by Emperor Janmejay to mark the site of the sacrificial pit, known as ''Parikshit kund'', still exists in [[Mainpuri]] district. This is known as Gowdvana. Close to this village a very large and high khera {{further explanation needed|date=May 2017}} containing the ruins of a fort and some stone sculptures has been found. It is said to date back to the time of Emperor Parikshit. A popular local legend is that as a consequence of the virtues of that sacrifice snakes are still harmless in this place and its neighborhood.
== Succession == According to ''Puranas'', Janamejaya was succeeded by his grandson Ashwamedatta Further in the lineage, are mentioned, Adhisima-krishna and Nichakshu. After the time of his successors, the dynasty came to an end.
