{{Infobox journal | title = Speculum | cover = SpeculumJournal.gif | editor = Sarah Spence | discipline = [[Medieval studies]] | abbreviation = Speculum | publisher = [[University of Chicago Press]] on behalf of the [[Medieval Academy of America]] | country = | frequency = Quarterly | history = 1926-present | openaccess = | impact = | impact-year = | website = http://www.medievalacademy.org/?page=Speculum | link1 = http://journals.uchicago.edu/spc | link1-name = Online access | JSTOR = 00387134 | OCLC = 35801878 | LCCN = 27015446 | CODEN = | ISSN = 0038-7134 | eISSN = 2040-8072 }} '''''Speculum: A Journal of Medieval Studies''''' is a quarterly [[academic journal]] published by [[University of Chicago Press]] on behalf of the [[Medieval Academy of America]]. It was established in 1926 and today is widely regarded as the most prestigious journal in medieval studies. The journal's primary focus is on the time period from 500 to 1500 in [[Western Europe]], but also on related subjects such as [[Byzantine]], [[Hebrew]], [[Arabic]], [[Armenian studies|Armenian]] and [[Slavic peoples|Slavic]] studies. {{As of|2016}}, the [[Editor-in-chief|editor]] is Sarah Spence.
The organization and its journal were first proposed in 1921 at a meeting of the [[Modern Language Association]], and the journal's focus was interdisciplinary from its beginning,<ref>{{cite journal|jstor=2913990|title=Reviewed Work(s): Speculum: A Journal of Mediaeval Studies. by The Mediaeval Academy of America|first=Edwin|last=Greenlaw|journal=[[Modern Language Notes]]|volume=41|issue=4|year=1926|pages=271–273}}</ref> with one reviewer noting a specific interest in [[Medieval Latin]].<ref>{{cite journal|title=Reviewed Work(s): Speculum|first=R. B.|last=McK.|journal=[[The Review of English Studies]]|volume=2|issue=7|year=1926|page=375|jstor=508377}}</ref>
